reis, Saxony, Germany","Chemnitz, Sachsen, Germany":"Chemnitz, Saxony, Germany","Grossrückerswalde,Marienberg,Sachsen,Deutschland":"Großrückerswalde, Mittlerer Erzgebirgskreis, Saxony, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Neumann","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Otto, Gunter, Helmut, Erwin, Heinz, Dieter, Guenter, Bernd, Ernst, Fritz.","German, Danish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a newcomer to a place, from Middle High German <i>niuwe</i> (German <i>neu</i>) ‘new’ + <i>man</i> (German <i>Mann</i>) ‘man’. This surname is also found in Czechia, Poland, Sweden, France (Alsace and Lorraine), and some other European countries."],"variants":[{"name":"Neiman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Moshe, Pincus, Chaim, Hershel, Sender, Avrohom, Baruch, Bronia, Elchonon, Eliyohu, Gershon, Hyman.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Neumann   ‘newcomer’. This form of the surname is also found in Sweden.","Americanized form of German   Neimann   ‘newcomer’."]},{"name":"Neeman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Aron, Giora, Menashe, Amnon, Limor, Moshe, Shaul.","Jewish: occupational name from a Hebrew term meaning ‘treasurer ofthe community’. In some cases this may represent a Hebraized (Israeli)form of   Neumann  ."]},{"name":"Naiman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Yosef, Ari, Chaya, Elimelech, Emanuel, Hyman, Isadore, Mayer, Shlomo, Yitzchok.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): Yiddish equivalent of German   Neumann   ‘newcomer’. Compare   Newman  ."]},{"name":"Naumann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Otto, Kurt, Erwin, Fritz, Horst, Joerg, Arno, Bernd, Bernhardt, Berthold, Egon.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Neumann  ."]},{"name":"Newman","meanings":["English (southern): nickname from Middle English <i>newe</i> ‘new’ (i.e. newly arrived or newly appointed) + <i>man</i> ‘man’ (Old English <i>nīwe</i> + <i>mann</i>).","Americanized form (translation into English) of surnames meaning ‘new man, newcomer’, for example German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Neumann  , Swedish   Nyman  , Polish   Nowak  , Czech or Slovak <b>Novák</b>, Slovenian, Croatian, or Serbian   Novak  ."]},{"name":"Newmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz, Markus.","Americanized form of German   Neumann  ."]},{"name":"Neimann","meanings":["German: variant of   Neumann   ‘newcomer’."]},{"name":"Nejman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jadwiga, Jerzy, Zygmunt.","Polish and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): of German origin, from the Polish adaptation of   Neumann  ."]},{"name":"Neuman","meanings":["Americanized form of German or Danish   Neumann  , and a variant of the same Jewish (Ashkenazic) surname. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia, Poland, Sweden, the Netherlands, and some other European countries."]},{"name":"Nayman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Esfir, Shmuel, Yakov.  Russian Lev, Mikhail, Oleg, Yelena.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Yiddish <i>nayman</i> ‘new man’(see   Neumann  )."]}]},{"name":"Christina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Simplified form of Latin <i>Christiana</i>, feminine form of <i>Christianus</i> (  see  Christian  ), or a Latinized form of Middle English <i>Christin</i> ‘Christian’ (Old English <i>christen</i>, from Latin)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Christina Neumann was born in 1530, in Großrückerswalde, Mittlerer Erzgebirgskreis, Saxony, Germany as the daughter of Adam Neumann. She married Bartel Gaertner on 1 July 1555, in Großrückerswalde, Mittlerer Erzgebirgskreis, Saxony, Germany. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1626, in Großrückerswalde, Amt Wolkenstein, Saxony, at the age of 96."},"et":{"1530–1626":"1530–1626","1525–